"1354","1352":"1352","1384":"1384","Abt 1378":"about 1378","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","abt. 1384":"about 1384","Ottringden, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","of Otterden, Kent, Eng.":"Otterden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Church","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name mostly found in southern and midland England, for someone who lived near a church, or possibly an occupational name for someone who worked at a church, such as a verger or sexton, from Middle English <i>chirche</i> ‘church’. The word comes from Old English <i>cyrice</i>, ultimately from medieval Greek <i>kyrikon</i>, for earlier <i>kyriakōn (dōma)</i> ‘(house) of the Lord’, from <i>kyrios</i> ‘lord’. Compare   Kirk  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Kirch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kirk","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Danish: from Middle English, Danish <i>kirk</i> ‘church’ (Old Norse <i>kirkja</i>), a topographic name for someone who lived near a church. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 16th century or earlier."]},{"name":"Kern","meanings":["German, Dutch, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>kerne</i> ‘kernel, seed, pip’; Middle Dutch <i>kern(e)</i>, <i>keerne</i>; German <i>Kern</i> or Yiddish <i>kern</i> ‘grain’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a farmer, or a nickname for a physically small person. As a Jewish surname, it is mainly artificial.","English (southeastern): metonymic occupational name for a maker or user of milk churns, from Middle English <i>kern</i>, <i>kirn</i>, <i>kurn</i>, a side-form of <i>chern</i> ‘churn’. Compare   Church  .","Slovenian: nickname for a stunted person, from an old spelling of <i>krn</i> ‘stunted’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Church was born about 1354, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with John Aucher."},"et":{"Abt 1354–":"umbes 1354–Surnud","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1382–1445":"1382–1445","1384–Female":"1384–Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1445":"1445","1378":"1378","Abt 1354":"umbes 1354","1376":"1376","1354":"1354","1352":"1352","1384":"1384","Abt 1378":"umbes 1378","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","abt. 1384":"umbes 1384","Ottringden, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Otterden, Kent, Eng.":"Otterden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1354–":"noin 1354–Kuollut","1352–Male":"1352–Kuollut","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1378–Male":"1378–Kuollut","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1382–1445":"1382–1445","1384–Female":"1384–Kuollut","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1445":"1445","1378":"1378","Abt 1354":"noin 1354","1376":"1376","1354":"1354","1352":"1352","1384":"1384","Abt 1378":"noin 1378","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","abt. 1384":"noin 1384","Ottringden, Kent, England":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Otterden, Kent, Eng.":"Otterden, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuninga